1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:27,253
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambhodassa

2
00:00:27,655 --> 00:00:34,003
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,024 --> 00:00:37,889
So we're on to the fifth of these parami, of these perfections.

4
00:00:40,072 --> 00:00:42,354
And this one is renunciation.

5
00:00:43,496 --> 00:00:44,037
Nikamma.

6
00:00:44,457 --> 00:00:51,368
N-E-K-K-H-A-M-M-A Just in case you want to remember it.

7
00:00:51,954 --> 00:01:21,826
it translates very well as renunciation now it's a key thing in Buddhist understanding renunciation and it's the moment it's symbolized in our practice through the Buddha's own the great renunciation that's what it's called it's that point where you know the vanity of life and the necessity of sickness old age and death finally get through to him and he leaves he leaves his home

8
00:01:22,076 --> 00:01:28,019
He leaves his wife, his child is just born, his young man, he's only, what, 29 when he goes.

9
00:01:28,700 --> 00:01:32,474
So we have this image of him getting on his horse,

10
00:01:33,046 --> 00:01:41,853
a cantica, I think his name was, with his servant Channa and riding off to the river, see, across the Rubicon.

11
00:01:42,454 --> 00:01:48,400
So it has this mythical image of, you know, crossing into another country, a river.

12
00:01:48,900 --> 00:01:52,905
And of course he would talk about Nibbana eventually as being the other shore.

13
00:01:53,965 --> 00:02:00,792
Anyway, he gets to the river, cuts off his hair, dons the rag robes of a mendicant and off he goes.

14
00:02:01,361 --> 00:02:07,311
His poor horse, Kantika, stricken by grief, dies.

15
00:02:09,955 --> 00:02:11,657
Little myths around that.

16
00:02:11,978 --> 00:02:14,162
But he's known as the Great Renunciation.

17
00:02:14,181 --> 00:02:15,362
He leaves everything, you see.

18
00:02:16,465 --> 00:02:28,163
And one of the practices that he does before he becomes liberated is, of course, he tries self-mortification, the mortification practices.

19
00:02:29,897 --> 00:02:58,284
and these were really based on the idea that desire arose mainly from the body so if you didn't eat then your desire for food went and so did your greed so they were pretty tough sort of practices to overcome the body thinking the body as being the problem and he practiced these in his usual way to the final degree

20
00:02:59,040 --> 00:03:04,106
And if you remember, he left his companions, his five companions, and they thought he'd gone soft.

21
00:03:06,430 --> 00:03:22,688
But his eventual description of these mortification exercises was dukkha anadyo anatasamito, which means ignoble, which means it's not on the path, it doesn't lead to liberation, useless, and suffering.

22
00:03:23,288 --> 00:03:28,254
So there he is, trying to get rid of suffering, and he's just piling it on with these

23
00:03:28,301 --> 00:03:33,468
the very heavy exercise of mortification.

24
00:03:37,153 --> 00:03:39,736
But renunciation is something different.

25
00:03:40,897 --> 00:03:48,748
Renunciation is stop doing something in order to discover your attachment.

26
00:03:49,088 --> 00:03:50,631
That's the purpose of renunciation.

27
00:03:51,504 --> 00:04:03,717
And one of the distinctions we can make these days is between fasting, which is a word people don't generally use these days, apart from fasting for health, and dieting.

28
00:04:04,799 --> 00:04:12,385
So the idea of fasting for health and dieting is, you know, you get your weight down so you can eat again, more.

29
00:04:13,768 --> 00:04:17,091
It's just a trick we play on ourselves.

30
00:04:17,375 --> 00:04:19,562
But that's not the spiritual point of fasting.

31
00:04:20,024 --> 00:04:27,029
Fasting was always to let go in order to see what your relationship was to what it was you were letting go of.

32
00:04:28,781 --> 00:04:37,009
So if we take renunciation in that very broad sense of the term, I mean, just look at your life and just catch what you're attached to, you see?

33
00:04:37,610 --> 00:04:49,240
And then just say, no, I'm not going to do it for a while, just to feel the amount of energy I'm putting into that particular object, that particular pleasure that I have.

34
00:04:51,302 --> 00:04:58,569
I mean, one of the things I, you know, have said to people is, choose your favorite program on TV, see?

35
00:04:59,139 --> 00:05:00,642
So some of you will be watching the World Cup.

36
00:05:03,528 --> 00:05:09,961
Just sit in front of the TV, get yourself a cup of tea and a biscuit and don't turn it on.

37
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:16,552
And just feel what happens when your program is on that you're normally unwrapped in.

38
00:05:17,555 --> 00:05:18,617
And you can take any

39
00:05:19,036 --> 00:05:38,394
anything that you're attached to, it doesn't matter, it could be going out of an evening, it could be DVDs, it could be a cup of tea, you know, I dread doing renunciation of a cup of tea, but if you just think of your, just as the desire comes up for something,

40
00:05:38,375 --> 00:05:48,798
And then you say no, but now it doesn't work unless you sit in silence, unless you actually turn into yourself and just feel the fire of that craving.

41
00:05:49,540 --> 00:05:50,322
You've got to feel it.

42
00:05:51,204 --> 00:05:56,214
And as the craving comes up, then that's telling you how attached you are to the object.

43
00:05:56,752 --> 00:06:00,439
Now, why would you want to get rid of an attachment to something which is giving you pleasure?

44
00:06:02,745 --> 00:06:15,451
It's because that sort of attachment is coming from an essential delusion of seeking happiness in pleasure, seeking happiness in the world.

45
00:06:16,326 --> 00:06:40,663
and we don't really want to stop that unless we see the aftermath so the aftermath of attachment to pleasurable things is frustration when you can't get it grief if you lose it boredom people these days you know the general as you say ordinary person doesn't connect boredom with pleasure

46
00:06:41,014 --> 00:06:47,326
And it's a big problem because the more bored you are, it means the more you'll be seeking pleasure.

47
00:06:48,166 --> 00:06:57,242
And boredom is the measure of the way that something that you've enjoyed has lost its oomph, has lost its buzz.

48
00:06:58,524 --> 00:07:02,211
So that's why you can't keep eating the same piece of chocolate.

49
00:07:02,232 --> 00:07:05,858
You've got to have it flavoured with orange or lemon or...

50
00:07:06,377 --> 00:07:27,846
there's always going to be variety so variety is the spice of life but it's also a real disease it brings about diseases and those diseases are this continual lack of satisfaction of gratification rather so you're always seeking for something stronger

51
00:07:27,826 --> 00:07:53,225
there's that grief if you lose it frustration if you don't get it and this constant underlying anxiety that you may lose it hence you get you know this massive insurance industry so unless we make that sort of connection with the happiness that we get from pleasure with the aftermath of it then of course renunciation doesn't make any sense see

52
00:07:54,673 --> 00:08:05,680
Now, there's a deeper reason for that renunciation, because as you pull away from the world, you're also discovering what is beyond the world.

53
00:08:06,470 --> 00:08:09,233
you're also discovering what is on that other shore.

54
00:08:09,894 --> 00:08:13,278
And that cannot be discovered so long as we're attached to this world.

55
00:08:14,100 --> 00:08:24,374
So the process of renunciation is also not simply a psychological therapy for addiction, for compulsive behavior.

56
00:08:24,793 --> 00:08:31,163
It's actually a spiritual insight because it's leading you to see that there is something other.

57
00:08:32,323 --> 00:08:35,008
This other shore, nirvana, what is it?

58
00:08:36,000 --> 00:09:02,817
so the practice of purification is absolutely essential you can't progress without some without understanding the role of renunciation in the spiritual path and if you look at any tradition any spiritual tradition you'll find that it's always leaving the world you're leaving the world

59
00:09:04,537 --> 00:09:30,087
think of anything you know Sufis Christian monks Christian ascetics they're always leaving the world now we then think well if we left the world we just you know become a sort of blob or something or a useless Egypt but of course this is a this is a sort of spiritual progress in which you are leaving the world but also developing a new relationship to the world

60
00:09:31,283 --> 00:09:51,333
and that relationship no longer has this false idea that it's going to bring you happiness because you found your happiness in something which is beyond the world the unconditioned when we come back into the world having made that then of course

61
00:09:51,567 --> 00:09:53,570
We act in the world with that wisdom.

62
00:09:54,291 --> 00:09:55,673
And that's exactly what the Buddha did.

63
00:09:56,774 --> 00:09:59,238
And it's exactly what anybody who's enlightened does.

64
00:09:59,298 --> 00:10:01,120
They always come back into the world.

65
00:10:01,740 --> 00:10:06,587
In the oxherding pictures of Zen, remember, you get to number nine and it's the circle.

66
00:10:06,947 --> 00:10:07,950
So that's the completion.

67
00:10:09,130 --> 00:10:14,097
But then in the tenth picture, the monk is coming back into the world.

68
00:10:15,326 --> 00:10:21,038
Now, although that's in the grand scheme of full liberation, we do it all the time.

69
00:10:22,241 --> 00:10:28,154
As you let go of something, you've also let go of some small compulsive behavior.

70
00:10:28,836 --> 00:10:32,123
That compulsive behavior is now put to better use.

71
00:10:32,143 --> 00:10:33,927
It turns into its opposite.

72
00:10:34,716 --> 00:10:45,234
So where there was compulsive behaviour, it's all about me, me, me, servicing me, me, me, it now moves outwards, it becomes you, you, you, them, them, them.

73
00:10:45,374 --> 00:10:54,028
So it moves from selfishness to generosity, aversion to love, cruelty to compassion.

74
00:10:54,168 --> 00:10:59,255
So there's always that coming back into the world, it's just a natural transformation.

75
00:11:01,817 --> 00:11:04,160
But renunciation is difficult.

76
00:11:04,402 --> 00:11:06,144
It's not easy.

77
00:11:06,605 --> 00:11:11,211
It's not something that anybody would do unless they saw some benefits.

78
00:11:13,134 --> 00:11:15,417
I mean, if you're an addict, you see the benefit.

79
00:11:15,477 --> 00:11:19,302
If you're an alcoholic, obviously you want to try and let go of that.

80
00:11:20,211 --> 00:11:34,513
But we don't see how addiction in our lives, with a small a, is actually the source of a lot of restlessness and suffering and the usual stuff that I've mentioned, frustration, grief, the whole lot.

81
00:11:34,533 --> 00:11:41,663
So renunciation is an absolute key virtue to develop.

82
00:11:41,812 --> 00:12:08,173
in our lives and you don't have to push it just very slowly and of course life itself you know as we move towards sickness old age and death is a natural renunciation you know and if you can't let go of life as you get older as we get older as we move towards the grave then of course it becomes a real pain a real suffering isn't it we have to grow we have to grow old with dignity

83
00:12:08,490 --> 00:12:33,552
and that dignity become natural if we can just find that easiness of releasing of just letting go this is the way it is I can only hope that my words have been of some assistance now through your constant effort at renunciation

84
00:12:33,922 --> 00:12:46,142
you will liberate yourselves from all suffering and achieve the great peace sooner rather than later.

